"1178":"1178","1155":"1155","about 1147":"circa 1147","10 June 1156":"10 juni 1156","Abt 1160":"circa 1160","Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, England":"Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ewyas, Herefordshire, England":"Ewias, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1140–1198":"about 1140–1198","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1155–1204":"1155–1204","1158–Male":"1158–Deceased","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1178–1236":"1178–1236","1085–1147":"1085–1147","1092–1156":"1092–1156","1198":"1198","Abt 1115":"about 1115","Abt 1158":"about 1158","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1092":"1092","Abt 1140":"about 1140","1204":"1204","1236":"1236","1147":"1147","1158":"1158","1156":"1156","1178":"1178","1155":"1155","about 1147":"about 1147","10 June 1156":"10 June 1156","Abt 1160":"about 1160","Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, England":"Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Ewyas, Herefordshire, England":"Ewias, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Ewyas was born about 1140, in Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Baron Robert FitzHarold d' Ewyas, was 56 and his mother, Sybil, was 49. He married Petronilla de Scudamore in 1156, in Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1198, in his hometown, at the age of 59."},"et":{"Abt 1140–1198":"umbes 1140–1198","1140–1198":"1140–1198","1155–1204":"1155–1204","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1178–1236":"1178–1236","1085–1147":"1085–1147","1092–1156":"1092–1156","1198":"1198","Abt 1115":"umbes 1115","Abt 1158":"umbes 1158","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1092":"1092","Abt 1140":"umbes 1140","1204":"1204","1236":"1236","1147":"1147","1158":"1158","1156":"1156","1178":"1178","1155":"1155","about 1147":"umbes 1147","10 June 1156":"10. juuni 1156","Abt 1160":"umbes 1160","Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, England":"Ewyas Harold, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ewyas, Herefordshire, England":"Ewias, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gl